      <div xml:id="beq3sc-d1e698">
        <head xml:id="beq3sc-d1e698-Hd1e4126">Quaestio 31 [Pembroke 236 Transcription]</head>
        <head xml:id="beq3sc-d1e698-Hd1e4129" type="question-title">
          Whether someone freely (gratuite) loving God 
          is able to merit or demerit according to the same measure.
        </head>
        <p xml:id="beq3sc-d1e698-d1e4132">
          Whether someone freely (gratuite) loving God 
          is able to merit or demerit according to the same measure.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="beq3sc-d1e698-d1e4143">
          That not because 
          opposites are not in the same thing, 
          therefore.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="beq3sc-d1e698-d1e4148">
          To the opposite, 
          the one who merits eternal life 
          earns merit, <!-- trans. check -->
          and whoever sins venially 
          earns demirt. 
          But someone is able to earn eternal life 
          and sin venially at the same time, 
          therefore, etc. 
        </p>
        <p xml:id="beq3sc-d1e698-d1e168">
          Therefore I say yes 
          and to the argument in the opposition 
          I say that to merit and demerit 
          with respect to the same prize
          are opposites, 
          otherwise they are not, 
          therefore the conclusion is true.
        </p>
      </div>
